                        "firstName": "Christian",
                        "lastName": "Eriksson",
                        "description": "Christian Eriksson, born 30 June 1858 at the farm Haget in Taserud, Arvika National Assembly, Värmland, died November 6, 1935 in the Maria Magdalena parish, Stockholm, was a Swedish sculptor.\r\nChristian Eriksson was the brother of furniture maker Elis Eriksson, father of sculptor Liss Eriksson and uncle of the artist Elis Eriksson. He was married in 1894-1911 with Jeanne Tramcourt and has with her son the sculptor Matts Eriksson.\r\nIn the mid-1870s, Christian Eriksson was an apprentice to an ornamental carpenter in Stockholm and studied at the Technical School at the same time. In 1877-1883, he worked as a furniture architect and modeling engineer at a furniture factory in Hamburg and then traveled to Paris, where he was a student at the École national supérieure des arts décoratifs and École nationale supérieure des Beaux-Arts and worked in Alexandre Falguiere's studio. To support himself, he helped other artists with modeling and marble cutting. In 1888 he exhibited the statue Martyren at the Paris Salon and received a medal and scholarship for his debut work. However, the real breakthrough came the following year with the bronze vase Tjusning, which today is available at the National Museum and in 1890 the vase Blindbock, today at the Gothenburg Art Museum. In 1891, the great plaster relief Linnaeus was added, which in 1894 was made in marble for the National Museum and was erected there.\r\nChristian Eriksson's works are characterized by freshness, originality, and often with elements of humor. He also made meritorious artifacts. Christian Eriksson has his resting place at Mikaelikyrkan \r\n"
