                        "description": "Willy Wulf Gordon, born July 2, 1918 in Reņģe, Russia, died July 12, 2003 in Stockholm, was a Swedish sculptor.\r\n\r\nWilly Gordon was born in the then Russian government of Kurland and brought the family to Malmö as a seven-year-old. He studied sculpture from 1940 to 1945 for Nils Sjögren at the Stockholm Academy of Fine Arts and later for Ossip Zadkine in Paris. He has mostly made himself known for his public works of art, which are found in about fifteen places in Sweden.\r\n\r\nWilly Gordon was active in Stockholm most of his life, and there are almost a dozen public sculptures, such as the Evert Taube statue at Riddarholmskajen (also a version in Grebbestad), Fruarna i Fruängen's center, Living ore outside LKAB's former headquarters at Karlavägen in Stockholm (also in Kiruna and at Physicum in Lund) and Flykten with Toran, originally a youth work from 1945, outside Stockholm's synagogue. At the Dramaten, as late as 2006, a portrait head was set up in bronze by Erland Josephson, originally in terracotta and from 1976. Most attention has been given to Gordon for his sculpture outside Östermalm's market hall, Meeting, which depicts a man wearing a piece of meat in front of one lying woman. The sculpture has caused protests and been vandalized on two occasions, most recently in December 2006.\r\n\r\nMany of Gordon's works depict, like meeting the human body, highly stylized, influenced by Zadkine, and also by a way that brings the thought of sculptors like Eric Grate and Henry Moore. He used crystalline and molecular structures in cells and rocks for original monumental works during the 1960s and 1970s. In the 1990s, he won, together with architect Tsila Zak, a competition for a memorial site in the Lithuanian capital Vilnius to honor the centuries-old Jewish culture of the city.\r\n\r\nHe was married to the artist and calligraphic artist Mona Gordon.\r\n"
