                        "description": "Nicodemus Tessin the Younger, born May 23, 1654 in Nyköping, died April 10, 1728 in Stockholm, was a Swedish architect and minister. \r\nHe is known as the castle architect behind Stockholm's castle and was one of the Baroque's great architects in Sweden. He was Stockholm's city architect between 1681 and 1715. Nicodemus Tessin the younger was born in Nyköping as son of Nicodemus Tessin the elder and Maria Persdotter Swahn. He was carried to the baptism by the widow Queen Maria Eleonora. Tessin attended the German school in Stockholm where he studied as an architect for the father. He showed early talent, and was drawn to a tribute to Charles XI printed. In 1664 he was enrolled during the Stockholm nation at Uppsala University, where he studied mathematics, French and Italian, and from 1671 he ended up under the widowed queen Hedvig Eleonora's protection, so he could go to Italy on a study trip in 1673.\r\nFor company he had the marquee del Monte, and they traveled via Germany to Verona, and visited Rome for a long time where Queen Kristina arranged for his education. Therefore he got to study for Lorenzo Bernini, as well as Carlo Fontana and Giovanni Pietro Bellori. As the Renaissance demanded, he received training in ancient aesthetics, especially the Roman. He returned to Sweden in 1678, and then had incomparable education, but was nevertheless sent to France and Louis XIV together with diplomat Daniel Cronström. From France, he received impetus and guidance from Charles Le Brun, André Le Nôtre and Jean Bérain. For a short time he stayed in England with Karl II where he came in contact with Christopher Wren. Several drawings have been preserved from these trips. \r\nIn 1680, Tessin was appointed leader of Hedvig Eleonora's buildings and was appointed chamberlain. In 1687–1688, he once again made his way to France and Italy, to draw inspiration from Drottningholm Castle's interior, when he became acquainted with Burchard Precht. The trip is documented in a diary. He had at that time succeeded the father as court and castle architect, and also became urban architect in Stockholm, the latter position together with his half-brother Abraham Winantz. On June 21, 1697, he was appointed as an overintendent, in 1701 to the Hull Marshal, and in 1705 to the Chief Marshal. For his efforts, he was elevated to dignified and dignified dignity.\r\nOver time, his administrative ambitions took over. In 1705 he became chancellor at Lund University and in connection with this he resigned as a city architect. Charles XII appointed him royal council and member of the Justice Review in 1712. His political career acquired him unfamiliar, and after Karl XII's death, he joined the Holstein Party and wanted to join an alliance with Russia, so in 1726 he ended up in despair and dismissed by Fredrik I. He died in 1728 and got a simple funeral in silence in Storkyrkan in Stockholm.\r\nNicodemus Tessin d.y. was the father of Carl Gustaf Tessin in his first marriage to Countess Hedvig Eleonora Stenbock. She died in 1714, and Tessin remarried in 1716 with the liberal professor Maria Barbro Horn of Marienborg, dead in 1725.\r\n"
