                        "description": "Bernt Notke, born about 1440 in Lassan , dead 1509,  was a North German painter and sculptor. He is considered one of the most significant artists of the late Middle Ages in Northern Europe.  Bernt Notke was active in Lübeck, where he became a master in 1467 and 1505 a master at Petri Church. Notke was also active in Stockholm between 1484 and 1496.\r\nOne of his more famous works is a famous painting series in Mariakyrkan in Lübeck. The painting series was destroyed when the church met during a bomb attack in 1942.\r\nThe most famous sculpture attributed to Notke is Sankt Göran and the dragon standing in Storkyrkan and as a replica at Köpmantorget, both in the Old Town in Stockholm. However, it is disputed whether the artwork is created by Notke or not, see the article of the sculpture.\r\nNotke was very productive and had great influence in Germany and Sweden. Fixed works by Notke are located in Sweden, Germany, Denmark and the Baltic States. Notke worked with an expressionist and intense style. His work is often very detailed.\r\nIn Estonia there is an altar cabinet from 1483 executed by him in the Holy Spirit Church (Püha Vaimu kirik) and his painting Death Dance in the Nikolaikyrik (Niguliste kirik), both in Tallinn's old town.\r\nIn addition, in 1477 he performed a triumphal crucifix for Lübeck's cathedral in 1477 and an altar work for Aarhus Cathedral in 1479. In Lübeck, he also performed a Luke altar and a St. John's wort, kept in Sankt-Annen-Kloster in Lübeck, the latter dated in 1496.\r\n"
